Description: An aphid parasitoid used as a biocontrol agent to help prevent large scale outbreaks and to generally reduce populations
Mode of action: Parasitism and consumption
LERAP Status: Not applicable
Other status (legislative: Most countries require a licence to be issued before non-native macro-organisms may be released as biocontrol agents
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied to growers as a mixture of pure mummies and freshly emerged adults with a food source.

Description: A specific strain of the bacterial insecticide Bt selected for its control of Coleoptera particularly the Colorado potato beetle
Mode of action: Stomach poison. Microbial disruptor of insect midgut membranes.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often supplied as a wettable powder or aqueous suspension which are applied as sprays. Frequent applications required.

Description: A Gram-negative plant pathogenic bacterium used to control fungal infections in stored produce
Mode of action: Exact mode of action unclear but thought to outcompete the fungi for space and nutrients on the fruit, thereby preventing the fruit from rotting before it can be used
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually applied as a drench, as a concentrate for producing a dip solution or as frezze-dried powders

Description: A naturally occurring fungus that can be used for controlling powdery mildew
Example pests controlled: Powdery mildew
Example hosts: Cucurbits; Some ornamentals
Mode of action: Acts by killing localised powdery mildew cells by releasing fatty acid substances that destroy the mildew membranes
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as a wettable powder or in a liquid formulation comprised of spores within an inert carrier and applied to foliage

Description: A fungus which acts as a biological herbicide and used to control mist flowers, Ageratina riparia - an invasive weed in tropical and temerate regions
Mode of action: Fungi produces spores on the underside of fresh leaves which causes plant dieback
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Not available commercially

Description: A non-pathogenic isolate of the bacterium Erwinia carotovora used to control soft rot disease
Mode of action: Out competes pathogens for potential invasion sites preventing the disease establishing
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as a suspension of spores that is mixed with water and used as a foliar spray

Isomerism: Brassinolide is a complex molecule with 13 chiral centres. It is the R-isomers of brassinosteroids that are, in general, more biologically active.
Description: A biologically active steroidal lactone first isolated from rape pollen that stimulates growth of green plant tissues.
Example pests controlled: Growth
Example hosts: Fruit including apples; pears, citrus; Rice; Wheat; Corn; Tomatoes: Cucumber; Lettuce
Mode of action: Oligodynamic and rapid, affects specific target tissues that are sensitive to the plant hormone indole-3-acetic acid (IAA)
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
OtherID6: King Tang Chemical Group; Jinan Haohua Industry Co; Duchefa Biochemie B.V.
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often supplied as a water soluble powder

Description: Substance prepared from the seed of a legume (Fenugreek) that has fungicidal properties
Mode of action: Stimulates the defense mechanisms in plants
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as a water soluble powder used as a foliar spray

Description: Naturally occurring substance, found in the stings and bites of some insects, that is used to treat tracheal and varroa mites in honey bee hives. It is also a pesticide transformation product
Mode of action: Not applicable
LERAP Status: Not applicable
Other status (legislative: Food and Feed additive as a acidity regulator (FLAVIS no. 08.001)
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: For bee hive applications it is formulated as an impregnated pad.

Efficacy & activity: Products containing these Bt strains have all been authorised at Member State level for > 10 years and demonstrated to be effective.
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often supplied as a granular formulation of endotoxin crystals and living spores which is mixed with water and applied as a spray. Frequent applications required.

Isomerism: A complex molecule with 8 chiral centres
Description: A plant growth regulator with a variety of uses including improving fruit set, increasing berry size and controlling fruit maturity
Example hosts: Seedless grapes
Mode of action: Has physiological and morphological effects on plant
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Molar mass: [EU 2019 dossier: Fumonisin B1, B2 total = 200 μg/kg]
OtherID6: ICI Plant Protection; Abbott; Nihon Nohyaku
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Available as granules, water-soluble tablets, soluble powders and soluble crystal formulations

Description: A natural compound, sourced from algae, that can be used to improve seed germination and protect against foliar fungal infections
Example pests controlled: Botrytis spp., Phytophthora spp.; Erwinia amylovora, Pseudomonas syringae
Example hosts: Lettuce; Vegetables; Tomatoes; Courgette; Pumpkin; Cucumber; Curcubits; Fruit including strawberries, apples, pears, grape, kiwi
Mode of action: Foliar absorbed and acts by stimulating the plants natural defense system - a systemic acquired resistence (SAR) inducer
Efficacy & activity: Shown to be efficatious via field trials in Belgium during 2008.
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as a wettable powder and used as a foliar spray

Description: A commonly occurring deuteromycetous fungal biopesticide effective against a range of Coleoptera insects
Mode of action: Entomopathogen, penetrating insect cuticle and invading haemolymph
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as a liquid concentrate or as granules

Isomerism: Milbemectin is a complex molecule with 10 chiral features. The technical material is a mixture of milbemycin A3 and milbemycin A4 in a ratio of 30:70,
Description: An insecticide and acaricide effective against all development stages of mites and some other insects
Example pests controlled: Spider mites; Tarsonemid mites; Leaf miners; Pinewood nematode
Example hosts: Soft fruit including Straweberry, blackberry, currants, raspberry, gooseberry; Apple, Pear, Cherry, Plum; Orange; Eggplants; Ornamentals
Mode of action: Contact and stomach action, acting on the targets nervous system
Efficacy & activity: Efficacy proven via field trials
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as an emulsifiable concentrate or wettable powder

Summary: Non-toxic to humans. Major environmental pathways include volatilisation and microbial degradation. Highly toxic to aquatic invertebrates but practically non-toxic to freshwater fish however minimal exposure would be expected. Not expected to be harmful to beneficial insects.
Description: An insect sex pheromone of the housefly used to trap flies in agricultural and domestic situations
Mode of action: As male populations are reduced, breeding cycle is disrupted resulting in less egg production and lower populations
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Used in traps, sticky paper and dispensers, product may include rapid knockdown insecticide

Isomerism: A chiral molecule. The technical material is a racemate composed of equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-nicotine.
Description: A general purpose, plant derived non-persistent insecticide
Example pests controlled: Aphids; Thrips; Whiteflies
Mode of action: Broad spectrum and fast acting nerve toxin. Mainly respiratory action but some contact and stomach activity
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often used as smoke generating formulations within glasshouses and potato chitting houses. Typically around 225g product per 560 cubic metres are used.

Description: An insecticidal baculovirus used for the control of a wide variety of lepidopteran species
Mode of action: Kills the insect larva following ingestion - causes hydrolysis of solid beta-chitin liquifying the infected host larvae.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as a liquid concentrate

Description: A bacterium isolated from cultivated soil used to control root-knot nematodes in glasshouse and field grown vegetable crops
Mode of action: Actual mode of action is complex using various mechanisms including enzymatic action, degradation of root exudates and the production of a phytohormone.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Available in a variety of formulations including dry powders and formulations for use as drenches, sprays and with drip irrigation systems

Mode of action: Not applicable
LERAP Status: Not applicable

Description: Substance used, post-harvest, as a catalytic generator for the production of ethylene gas for fruit ripening. It has bactericidal activity and is used often as a topical disinfectant.
Mode of action: Chemical reaction
LERAP Status: Not applicable
Other status (legislative: EC 2232/96 Annex 1 registered as food flavouring agent, UK registered Commodity Substance
CIPAC number: Metabolite, Other substance, Plant growth regulator precursor, Additive, Insecticide
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Not applied directly to the crop. Usually used via immersion in a tank enclosed in a fume cupboard

Description: Chemical transformation product and toxicologcally relevant product impurity
Mode of action: Not applicable
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: A chemical transformation product with strong fungicidal activity
Example pests controlled: Phytophthora infestans
Example hosts: Tomato
Mode of action: Not applicable
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: Chemical transformation product
Mode of action: Not applicable
LERAP Status: Not applicable

Description: Volatile aliphatic monoterpine emitted from plants on wounding that is known to prevoke a behavioural response in several parasitoids and predators of plant herbivores
Mode of action: Long lasting activity, contact action
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Other status (legislative: EC 2232/96 Annex 1 registered as food flavouring agent

Description: A naturally occurring chemical that acts as a beetle repellent when applied to trees by signalling a food and habitat source
Mode of action: Contact
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Other status (legislative: EC 2232/96 Annex 1 registered as food flavouring agent

Description: A naturally occuring aggressive fungal parasite used in glasshouses and in the field to control a variety of insect pests
Mode of action: Contact action, acts by rapidly destroying the internal structures of the host insect killing it
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Formulations are often emulsifiable suspensions and wettable powders which are used as aqueous sprays

Description: A soil fungus used to control plant parasitic nematodes in a range of field and protected crops
Example pests controlled: Various plant parasitic nematodes including root knot, root lesion and potato cyst nematodes
Example hosts: Tomato; Cucumber
Mode of action: Spores of the fungus are parasites of the eggs and larvae of the nematodes reducing populations
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Formulation is often as water soluble granules which are then used as soil spray, drip irrigation or drench.

Description: A forestry biofungicide used for the control of root and butt rot in coniferous trees
Example hosts: Conifer forests
Mode of action: Fungus invades cut tree surfaces preventing the subsequent invasion by the rot-causing organisms, particularly H. annosum.
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as a wettable powder which is mixed with water and sprayed onto trees immediately after felling. 8-68 g/ha (approx 1-2 g/m2 stump surface), applied once during each harvesting period

Description: A biological insecticide used to control sucking insect pests usually on protected crops
Mode of action: Contact action, destroys the insect tissue via fungal growth
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often formulated as a wettable powder, solutions are applied at high volumes. Highest efficacy under humid conditions, typically 1.25 kg product in 250 litres water per ha spray

Description: A baculovirus used to control Codling moth in top fruit and nut orchards
Mode of action: Highly specific, the virus is injested by feeding larva which then rapdily die and breakdown
LERAP Status: None
Minimum active substance purity: Cydia pomonella granulosis virus Mexican and French isolates
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as liquid and suspension concentrates, used as high volume spray applications. 1.0E+13 GV per ha, up to 3 applications may be required

Description: A botanically derived insect growth regulator used to control a range of insects. Also reported to have some fungicidal activity
Mode of action: Inhibits juvenile hormone biosynthesis
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Summary: Citosan is an animal-derived pesticide that is approved for use in some countries but not in the EU. There is limited data available for its environmental fate. It has a low mammalian oral toxicity and no significant health effects have been identified. Limited data is available regarding its ecotoxicity but it is known to have a high toxicity to fish.
Description: An animal derived fungicide used to control root rots and a plant growth regulator used to improve seed germination, root development and general plant health
Mode of action: Boosts the ability of plants to defend against fungal infections
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as an aqueous suspension or in a pelleted formulation

Description: A inorganic-copper fungicide and microbiocide derived from chlorophyll
Mode of action: Unknown
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: A plant growth regulating substance used on top fruit and ornamentals to maximise yields
Mode of action: Inhibits the biosynthesis of ethylene
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as a water soluble concentrate applied up to two weeks before harvest

Isomerism: Azadirachtin is a molecule with 16 chiral centres. Azadirachtin extracts are mainly comprised of azadirachtin A but other isomers (e.g. B, H & J) may also be present.
Description: A potent tetranortriterpenoid botanical insecticide active against a wide range of insect pests. It also has some fungicidal properties
Mode of action: Interrupts pests hormonal system. Disrupts insect mouting and will also smother and desiccate insects
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Molar mass: [Many different substances in the plant extract including azadirachtin B, azadirachtin H & aflatoxins]
Other constituents in formulations 6: Azatin-Plus EC; Azatin EC; Margosan-O; Agroneem Plus; Aza-Direct; NeemAzal
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as an emulsifiable concentrate and applied as a spray

Description: A Gram-positive bacterium insecticide, widespread in soil and used to control mosquito larvae
Mode of action: Biological activity - spore-forming bacterium toxic to the target. Microbial disruptor of insect midgut membranes. Ineffective on adult mosquitoes
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Minimum active substance purity: Bacillus sphaericus Neide Var. Serotype H5a5b, strain 2362
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often supplied as water dispersible granules which are mixed with water and applied as a spray. Frequent applications required.

Description: Used  to control a wide range of economically important fungal and bacterial diseases.
Mode of action: Bacteria colonise root system competing with disease. Microbial disruptor of insect midgut membranes.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Minimum active substance purity: Bacillus subtilis Cohn, var. Amyloliquefaciens strain GB03
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as a soluble concentrate and used as a foliar spray, but also available as seed treatments and seed drenches

Description: A microbial fungicide used lawns, top fruit and rice to control various pathogenic fungi including Alternaria spp. and  Botrytis spp.
Mode of action: Systemic with protective action, inhibits cell wall biosynthesis
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as a wettable powder, emulsifiable concentrate or soluble granules

Description: A rodenticide that is most effective against Norway rats but also used to control black rats, house mice, field mice, and field voles
Mode of action: Toxin with stomach action, causes emesis and affects the rodents cardiovascular and central nervous system
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Isomerism: A chiral molecule. The technical material is a mixture of spinosyn A and D.
Description: An insecticide derived from naturally occurring soil fungi (naturalyte) used to control Lepidoptera
Example pests controlled: Thrips; Gypsy moth; Leaf beetles; Tent caterpillars
Example hosts: Onions & Leeks; Corn; Sweetcorn; Maize; Lettuce; Leafy vegetables; Potato; Eggplants; Pepper; Tomato; Celery; Fruit including grapes, cane fruits, berries, currants; Herbs & edible flowers
Mode of action: Contact and stomach action. Acts by exciting the insect nervous system, leading to involuntary muscle contractions and paralysis.
LERAP Status: Buffer probably required in UK - see product label
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often supplied as a soluble concentrate that is mixed with water and used as a spray

Isomerism: A complex chiral molecule. The technical material is an isomeric mixture of 8 isomers - 4 trans (A, B1, B2 & C) and 4 cis (V, W, V, Y) forms. Isomer C is the most attractive to Mediterranean fruit flies
Description: A synthetic pheromone insect attractant used to control fruit flies
Example pests controlled: Mediterranean fruit flies
Mode of action: Attractant
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied into slow release formulations

Description: An antibiotic with fungicide action effective against soil borne diseases and is used for the control of Rhizoctonia solani
Example pests controlled: Sheath blight disease
Example hosts: Rice; Potatoes; Vegetables; Cotton; Sugarbeet
Mode of action: Non-systemic, inhibits enzyme trehalase
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as a dispersible powder, soluble concentrates and seed treatments

Description: Naturally occuring substance used for the biological control of codling moth and other insects
Mode of action: Distrupts mating
LERAP Status: None
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied in slow release containers that emit the phermone as a vapour. Spray formulations are also available.

Description: Multi-action pesticide used to control downy mildew, powdery mildew, aphids and mites. Also used as a mammal repellant.
Example pests controlled: Dry bubble (Verticillium fungicola (Preuss) Hassebrauk; Dollar spot; Pitch canker; Various Verticillium, Rhizoctonia and Pythium species,
Example hosts: Mushrooms; Row crops; Ornamenatls; Turf; Pine forests
Mode of action: Absorbed via root system
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as a wettable powder

Description: A naturally synthesised herbicide that is usually used as the sodium salt
Mode of action: Non-selective, systemic, contact action. Glutamine synthetase inhibitor: accumulates ammonium ions, inhibits photosynthesis.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually suplied as a soluble powder or as liquid formulations

Description: Used to control a wide range of annual and perennial broad-leaved weeds in a variety of crops including vines and top fruit.
Mode of action: Non-selective, systemic, contact action. Glutamine synthetase inhibitor: accumulates ammonium ions, inhibits photosynthesis.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: A pheromone used to control Pink bollworms in cotton crops
Mode of action: Insect attractant used to distrupt mating
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as slow release formulations but spray formulations are also available

Summary: A botanical extract that can be used as a plant growth regulator for use indoors but which does not have EU approval for use. It is highly soluble in water and volatile. Little is known about its environmental persistance but there are indications that it may be persistent under certain conditions in water. However, it is unstable in UV light. It is moderately toxic to mammals but generally not thought to present significant risk of causing problems for human health although there are uncertainties regarding its effect for reproduction and the CNS. Little is known regarding its ecotoxicology.
Description: A botanical auxin extract used to improve rootings of woody plant cuttings
Mode of action: Broad spectrum, effects cell division and elongation stimulating the formation of roots.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Summary: Dicamba is a selective, systemic herbicide approved for use in the EU and used for general weed control. Summary: Abamectin is a bacterium-derived pesticide that is approved for use in many countries. It has a low aqueous solubility and is not volatile. It does not tend to be persistent in the environment. It has a highly oral toxicity to mammals and there is some evidence that it may induce negative reproduction effects at high doses. It exhibits high or medium toxicity to most fauna and flora.
Isomerism: A chiral molecule - abamectin is a mixture containing ~80% avermectin B1a and ~20% avermectin B1b.
Description: Abamectin is a natural fermentation product of this bacterium and acts as a selective acaricide, nematicide and insecticide for use in a wide variety of crops

Example hosts: Ornamental plants; Fruit including citrus, pears, tomatoes, watermelon; Cotton, Vegetable crops including eggplant, curcubits, beans;
Mode of action: Contact and stomach action with limited systemic activity, blocks electrical activity in nerves and muscles of pest
Efficacy & activity: Efficacy has been widely evaulated and proven to be excellent.

Summary: Difenoxuron is a selective, post-emergence herbicide that is no longer approved for use in many countries including the EU. It is not considered to be toxic to honeybees.

Summary: Dicloran is a fungicide that is not approved for use in the EU. It has a low aqueous solubility and is volatile. Based on its chemical properties, is may leach to groundwater. It can also be quite persistent in soils but not usually so in water. It is moderately toxic to mammals but is not expected to bioaccumulate. Exposure may damage reproduction and/or development. Dicloran is moderately toxic to most aquatic organisms, birds, honeybees and earthworms.

Summary: Dicofol is an organochloride acaricide that is not approved for use in the EU. Summary: Dicyclopentadiene is manufacturered from high temperature cracking of petroleum fractions in an ethylene manufacturing process. It has a low aqueous solubility, is highly volatile and flammable, and may be environmentally persistent. It is moderately toxic to mammals via ingestion but  more so if the vapour is inhaled. It may cause chemical burns in contact with the skin and is a recognised irritant. It is moderately toxic to many animal and plant species..

Summary: Diethofencarb is a carbamate fungicide that is approved for use in the EU. It has a low aqueous solubility and is volatile. Summary: Difenacoum is a 2nd generation anticoagulant rodentcide that is not approved for use in many countries. In water systems the predominant degradation process is photolysis. it is highly toxic to mammals with some evidence indicating that it may cause negative reproduction and/or fertiliy effects. There are gaps in ecotoxicological data but it is known to be highly toxic to birds and fish and moderately toxic to aquatic invertebrates.

Summary: Dimethametryn is a rice herbicide without EU regulatory approval for use. It tends to be persistent in soil systems and may also persist in aqueous systems. It is not susceptible to hydrolysis. It has a low mammalian toxicity and is a recognised irritant. It is moderately toxic to fish, aquatic invertebrates and honey bees.
Isomerism: Dimethametryn is a chiral molecule and the technical material is an isomeric mixture.
Description: Used to control broad-leaved weeds and grasses in rice and other crops
Example pests controlled: Couch grass; Crabgrass; Pigweed
Example hosts: Rice; Vegetables including cabbage, aubergine; Tomatoes; Tea; Sugarcane
Mode of action: Selective, absorbed by roots and foliage. Inhibits photosynthesis (photosystem II).
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Summary: Amicarbazone is a triazolone herbicide that is not approved for use in the EU. It is highly soluble and there is a high risk of leaching to groundwater.  It is volatile, non-persistent in soil but persistent in aquatic systems. It is moderately toxic to mammals and their is some risk of bioaccumulation. It is a respiratory tract and eye irritant but no other serious human health issues have been reported. It is moderately toxic to birds and honeybees.
Description: A triazolone, selective herbicide for pre- and post-emergence control of annual dicotyledonous weeds and grasses
Example pests controlled: Creeping bentgrass; Kentucky bluegrass; Fescue; Ryegrass
Example hosts: Turf including golf courses, sod farms, lawns, sports fields; Ornamentals including Christmas trees; Sugarcane
Mode of action: Contact action, absorbed by foliage, photosynthesis II inhibition
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Isomerism: Lactofen is a chiral molecule with an asymmetrically substituted C atom resulting in a pair of of enantiomers. The herbicidal activity predominately comes from the S-isomer.

Example pests controlled: Broad-leaved weeds
Example hosts: Cotton; Soybeans; Snap beans; Cotton; Forestry

LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
OtherID6: AgroCare; Makhteshim Agan Group; FCC Ltd
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as an emulsifiable concentrate

Summary: Flumiclorac-pentyl is a herbicide without EU regulatory approval for use. It tends not to be persistent in soil and aquatic systems degrading by both hydrolysis and photolysis. It has a low mammalian toxicity and is a recognised irritant. It is moderately toxic to fish and aquatic invertebrates, and relatively non-toxic to honey bees.

It is moderately toxic to birds, most aquatic organisms and earthworms but is not toxic to honeybees.

Summary: Sulfoxaflor is a new insecticide that is used to control aphids in field crops and favourably compares with imidacloprid in efficiacy. Summary: Dimethoate is an organophosphate insecticide no longer approved for use in the EU and in other parts of the world. It is highly soluble in water, has low groundwater leaching potential and is volatile. It is non-persistent in soil, mobile but does not normally persist in aerobic aquatic systems. It is moderately toxic to mammals but may have serious health implications for humans as it is an acetyl cholinesterase inhibitor and may cause reproduction or development effects. It is highly toxic to birds and honeybees, moderately toxic to most aquatic species and earthworms.

Summary: Amitraz is an amidine acaricide and insecticide that is currently not approved for use in the EU but is still used in some parts of the world. It is not persistent in soil systems, degradation being very rapid and would also not be expected to persistent in surface water under normal conditions. Amitraz has a moderate mammalian toxicity and there is some concern regarding its potential for bioaccumulation. It is considered to be a neurotoxin. Amitraz has a high to moderate toxicity to most terrestrial and aquatic species, the main exception being algae for which amitraz has a low level of toxicity.

LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Other status (legislative: Evidence of use in third world countries; Chemical subject to PIC regulations
Insecticide Resistance (IRAC) Classifica: [Agrotis ipsilon], [Blattella germanica], [Boophilus microplus], [Culex pipiens pallens], [Dendrolimus punctatus], [many others]
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Available in a range of formulations including soluble powders, soluble concentrates, granules and spot-on sticks.

Description: An insecticide used to protect against a range of insect pests. It is also used as an ecoparasitic treatment in veterinary medicine.
Example pests controlled: Flea larvae; Immature cockroaches; Sliverfish; Lice; Miosquitoes; beetles
Example hosts: Fruit including apples, pears, nectarines, peaches; Non-cropped situations including households, commercial and industrial sites
Mode of action: Chitin synthesis inhibitor, Insect growth regulator
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Other status (legislative: Evidence of use in third world countries
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often supplied as a suspension concentrate that is mixed with water and used as a spray but available in many other formulations such as pour-ons.

Summary: Cymiazol is an acaricide without EU regulatory approval for use. It is moderately  soluble in water and volatile. It does not tend to be persistent in soil systems but may be in some water systems. It is not susceptible to hydrolysis. It is moderately toxic to mammals and may bioaccumulate. It is an eye and skin irritant. It shows a moderate level of toxicity to birds, fish and honey bees.
Description: An acaricide used for the control of mites and ticks especially those resistant to organochlorines, organophosphates and carbamates
Example pests controlled: Livestock mites; Ticks; Fleas; Lice; Dung beetles; Varroa mites; Livestock flies
Example hosts: Livestock; Beehives; Agricultural buildings
Mode of action: Contact, detachant
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Isomerism: A chiral molecule. The technical material is an isomeric mixture.
Description: Used as a livestock insecticide and as an acaricide on citrus fruits, deciduous fruits and nuts
Example pests controlled: Ticks; Fleas; Lice; Mites including clover mites, spider mites; Thips; Apple maggots; Codling moth
Example hosts: Fruit including citrus, quince, grapes, apples, pears; Walnuts; Ornamentals; Non-agricultural sites such as industrial areas, recreational land, dog kennels
Mode of action: Acetylcholinesterase (AChE) inhibitor.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as an emulsifiable concentrate

Description: An obsolete contact organophosphate insecticide that was mainly used to control warble fly larvae
Example pests controlled: Cockroaches; Flies
Example hosts: Livestock housing; Dairies; Food storage areas; Poultry sheds; Refuse tips
Mode of action: Systemic, Cholinesterase inhibitor.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Supplied in a wide variety of different formulations incuding emulsifiable concentrates and granules

Description: Substance with no pesticidal properties but sometimes used in pesticide product formulations to form a barrier film preventing target pests from reaching plant.
Example pests controlled: Flea beetles; Japanese beetles; Sawflies; Codling moth; Aphids; Weevils; Psyllids; Thrips
Example hosts: Fruit including pears, apples, plums, cherries, grapes, berries; Row field crops
Mode of action: Mainly non-toxic mode of action, acts via its physical properties but may also interfere with feeding behaviou and egg-laying
LERAP Status: Not applicable

Isomerism: S-methoprene is the trans-form of the chiral methoprene and is more biologically active that the cis-form.
Description: An insect growth regulator used to control a range of common pests including ants, fleas and ticks
Example pests controlled: Diptera; Hymenoptera; Lepidoptera; Coleoptera spp.
Mode of action: A juvenile hormone mimic (terpene). Contact and stomach action, acts by mimicing the action of the juvenile hormone keeping the insect in an immature state
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Other constituents in formulations 6: Biopren-BM; Altosid; Apex; Diacon II; Pharaoh's Ant Colony Eliminator

Isomerism: Prallethrin is a complex chiral molecule. The technical material is an isomeric mixture of 8 stereoisomers but consists mainly of [1R,trans; S] and [1R,cis; S] isomers in a ratio of approximately 4:1..
Description: Many used to control insects in domestic and public health situations
Example pests controlled: Houseflies; Mosquitoes; Cockroaches; Ants; Fleas; Ticks
Example hosts: Public health applications; Households
Mode of action: Contact, with rapid knock down effect, acts on the insects nervous system
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Various formulations are available including oils, foams and plug in vapourisers

Description: An insecticide which is a component of permethrin, active against a wide range of pests including Lepidoptera and Coleoptera in crops and various animal ectoparasites
Example pests controlled: Cockroaches; Termites; Ticks; Mosquitoes; Aphids; Fleas; Ants
Example hosts: Fruit; Vegetables; Cotton; Ornamentals; Potatoes; Cereals
Mode of action: Broad spectrum with contact and stomach action. Slight repellant effect. Sodium channel modulator.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Available in a variety of formulations including fumigants, shampoos and spot-on treatments.

Description: An obsolete pre-emergence thiocarbamate herbicide that also has insecticide activity and was used as an ectoparasiticide
Example pests controlled: Most annual weeds; Ticks; Mites; Mange; Lice
Example hosts: Onions; Beans; Livestock; Humans
Mode of action: Contact, inhibition of lipid synthesis
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: An obsolete insecticide that was used to control a range of insect pests including ticks and mites
Example pests controlled: Mange and other mites; Ticks; Fleas; Aphids
Mode of action: Cholinesterase inhibitor
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as an emulsifiable concentrate for sprays or plunge dips

Description: An obsolete insecticide active against a wide range of pests including Lepidoptera and Coleoptera in crops and various animal ectoparasite
Example pests controlled: Moths; Various beetles; Ticks; Mites
Example hosts: Cotton; Wheat; Maize; Alfalfa
Mode of action: Neurotoxin, acts on the nervous system of insects, and disturbs the function of neurons by interaction with the sodium channel.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: A multi-use chemical that is now largely obsolete that had fungicidal, wood preservation and veterinary applications
Example pests controlled: Bacteria; Moulds; Yeasts
Example hosts: Beans; Ornamentals
Mode of action: An uncoupler of oxidative phosphorylation
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Isomerism: Quintiofos is a chiral molecule occurring in both the S- and R-forms.
Description: A largely obsolete substance that was used to control a range of plant and livestock pests
Example pests controlled: Aphids; Spidermites; Cockroaches; Mosquitoes; Ticks
Example hosts: Cotton; Non-cropped situations including residents and public buildings
Mode of action: Acetylcholinesterase (AChE) inhibitor
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: An obsolete herbicide that was used, pre-emergence/pre-sowing to control grass weeds
Example pests controlled: Couch; Millet; Wild oats; Foxtails
Example hosts: Field crops
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as an aqueous solution

Description: An obsolete insecticide once used for personal protetcion against insects
Example pests controlled: Mosquitoes; Gnats; Fleas; Midges; Chiggers
Example hosts: Humans; Livestock
Mode of action: Repellency
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied in ready-to-use formulations such as aerosols, creams and oil-based solutions

Summary: Imidacloprid is an insecticide approved for use in the EU with certain restrictions for flowering crops. It is highly soluble, non-volatile and persistent in soil. It is moderately mobile. It has a low risk of bioaccumulating. It is highly toxic to birds and honeybees. Moderately toxic to mammals and earthworms. It is non-toxic to fish.
Isomerism: Isomeric - existing as both the E- and Z- forms however many commerical products are comprised of almost entirely the (E)-isomer
Description: A chloronicotine insecticide used to control sucking and soil insects. Also used as a flea treatment for domestic pets.
Example pests controlled: Plant hoppers, Aphids, Termites, Colorado bettle, Fleas, White grups, Craneflies; Crickets, Ants
Example hosts: Lawns and turf; Domestic pets; Rice, Cereals; Maize; Potatoes; Sugar beet
Mode of action: Systemic with contact and stomach action. Acetylcholine receptor (nAChR) agonist.
LERAP Status: None
Other status (legislative: NOTE ban or usage restriction may be in place for use on flowering crops in some Member States
Insecticide Resistance (IRAC) Classifica: [Aphis gossypii], [Myzus persicae], [Phorodon humuli], [Sogatella furcifera], [Bemisia argentifolii], [many others]
Other constituents in formulations 6: Admire; Chinook Blue; Tripod Plus; Gaucho; Raxil
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Often supplied as granules that are mixed with water and applied as a spray, used as a seed treatment or applied directly to compost. For animal use it is usually supplied as a spot-on solution.

Description: A fungicide used to control scald and other diseases, post-harvest in top fruit normally used in enclosed areas
Example pests controlled: Scald
Example hosts: Top fruit
Mode of action: Anti-oxidant effecting plant growth
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Other status (legislative: Chemical subject to PIC regulations; Should not be used on Red Delicious, Golden Delicious or late picked Winesap apples as may reduce quality
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as an emulsifiable concentrate

Description: Mainly used as a non-agricultural pesticide with some veterinary applications as well as being used as a food additive and in perfumary.
Example pests controlled: Chiggers; Ticks; Mosquitoes; Gnats; House dust-mite; Human scabies
Example hosts: Non-agricultural situations; Public health situations; Domestic houses; Veterinary premises and hospitals; Textiles
Mode of action: Attacks the nervous system of mites
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
CIPAC number: Acaricide, Insecticide, Veterinary substance, Other substance
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Veterinary formulations are usually emulsions for topical application. Non-agricultural formulations include foams and powders.

Description: Used as an antifouling substance in marine paint and as a general anaesthetic as a sedative and analgesic drug for a variety of animals.
Example pests controlled: Barnacles; Tube worms; Fungi; Algae
Example hosts: Paint
Mode of action: A non-narcotic alpha2-adrenoreceptor agonist
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009

Description: A compound which acts as an insecticide synergist, increasing the potency of the active substance against a broad range of insect pests
Example pests controlled: Tick larvae; Lice; Mites
Mode of action: Thought to inhibit the metabolic detoxification via the P-450 monoxygenation
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
CIPAC number: Insecticide synergist; Veterinary substance; Other substance

Description: An obsolete rodenticide synergist used to enhance the effectiveness of warfarin
Example pests controlled: Rats; Mice
Example hosts: Rats; Mice
Mode of action: Bactericide action, kills vitamin K-producing bacteria in the rat intestine
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as bait

Description: A chemical degradation product and veterinary drug
Mode of action: Inhibits enzymatic reactions
LERAP Status: Not applicable
Pesticide type: Soil, Animal, Surface water, Groundwater, sediment

Description: Naturally occurring substance that is produced by a soil bacterium and which is active against certain fungal diseases
Mode of action: The substance binds to ergosterol, a building block in cell walls of yeasts and moulds, which damages the cell wall leading to death.
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually formulated as a wettable powder. For crop protection the product is used as a dip for bulbs. As a veterinary product it is usually applied topically.

Description: A plant derived terpene oil used mainly as an insect repellent and for the control of fleas and cockroaches in a variety of situations.
Mode of action: Contact poision for insects causing a neurotoxic effect
LERAP Status: No UK approval for use as a pesticide under EC Regulation 1107/2009
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Available as ready-to-use formulations such as sprays, powders and foggers. Activity against mosquitoes is questioned

Isomerism: Propetamophos is a chiral molecule. The technical material tends to consist  of 4 isomer: 2 geometric isomers (cis & trans) and 2 optical isomers (S- and R-). The S-form is the dominate isomer and usually exceeds 90% of the techinal material.
Description: A insecticide and acaricide for use in public health and livestock situations
Example pests controlled: Cockroaches; Flies; Ants; Moths; Fleas; Ticks; Mosquitoes; Termites
Example hosts: Public health applications; Landscape management; Non-cropped areas including rights-of-way, footpaths
Mode of action: Contact and stomach action with long residual activity; Acetylcholinesterase (AChE) inhibitor.
LERAP Status: Not applicable
Other status (legislative: Marine, Surface and Groundwater Pollutant; PAN listed Highly Hazardous Chemical
Insecticide Resistance (IRAC) Classifica: [Blattella germanica], [Bulex pipiens molestus], [Bulex pipiens pipiens], [Musca domestica], [Rhipicephalus bursa]
Ex Manufacturers of products using this: Usually supplied as a liquid concentrate for application as spot, surface, and crack and crevice treatments via low pressure spray or injected into the soil for termites.
